</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1513,1610]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1608130918" country="Mexico" location="Pacific region" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" specimenCount="1">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Stephens" authorityYear="1828" box="[285,388,1514,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hygrotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[285,388,1514,1537]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Hygrotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as here defined includes 129 described species (two of them bitypic) distributed in the Nearctic (including the north of 
<collectingCountry box="[524,615,1549,1574]" name="Mexico" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">MeXico</collectingCountry>
), Palaearctic, Afrotropical and Oriental zoogeographical regions (
<figureCitation box="[1368,1436,1549,1574]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[208,1378,197,1919]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[189,1396,193,1921]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendrogram showing the new classification of Hygrotini. A number of species without molecular data (no voucher number) have been inserted near morphologically similar species with molecular data. Acronyms refer to biogeographical regions." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/884770/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
and 
<tableCitation box="[198,280,1585,1610]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[125,200,512,532]" captionText="TABLE 1. Checklist of all 137 species of Hygrotini with original, new and former (Nilsson &amp; Há ek 2017 a) generic and subgeneric names; last three columns indicating new combinations, distribution and methods applied to material studied. See Villastrigo et al. (in press) for details on the specimens used in the molecular phylogeny and accession numbers of the sequences." pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Table 1</tableCitation>
). One Nearctic species was introduced to Hawaii (see below), which belongs to the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:039C87CE0F30FF92FF1F6601CAB05606:8EEA60030F30FF92FB416550CD59570A" box="[1225,1385,1585,1610]" country="Mexico" name="Pacific region" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Pacific region</location>
.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="518" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1657,1862]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1657,1682]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
In the new classification 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Stephens" authorityYear="1828" box="[635,738,1658,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hygrotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[635,738,1658,1681]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Hygrotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the second of two genera of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Portevin" authorityYear="1929" box="[1242,1355,1657,1682]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hygrotini">Hygrotini</taxonomicName>
. As in 
<taxonomicName authority="Fery, 2017" authorityName="Fery" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,257,1693,1718]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Clemnius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[151,257,1693,1718]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Clemnius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[263,342,1693,1718]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[263,335,1693,1718]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">n. gen</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
all species of the genus have two carinae in each antennal cavity (see 
<figureCitation box="[1129,1230,1693,1718]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 3 – 4" captionStart-1="FIGURES 5 – 6" captionStartId-0="13.[151,264,1658,1680]" captionStartId-1="14.[151,264,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox-0="[353,1132,193,1614]" captionTargetBox-1="[264,1323,403,1909]" captionTargetId-0="figure@13.[353,1233,193,1614]" captionTargetId-1="figure@14.[264,1323,403,1909]" captionTargetPageId-0="13" captionTargetPageId-1="14" captionText-0="FIGURES 3 – 4. Antennal cavities of: (3) Hydroporus dorsalis (Hydroporini) and (4) Hygrotus (Leptolambus) lagari (Fery, 1992) (a: carina delimiting capsule for scape; b: fronto-lateral border of clypeus; c: second carina)." captionText-1="FIGURES 5 – 6. SEM micrographs with details of head and antennal cavities of: (5) Hygrotus (Leptolambus) impressopunctatus (frontal view) and (6) Hygrotus (s. str.) inaequalis (oblique ventral view) (a, b and c as in Figs 3 – 4; d: clypeal stripe; e: labrum)." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/884772/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/884774/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Figs 4–6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1657,1862]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">
According to the two main clades in the phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Portevin" authorityYear="1929" box="[839,948,1729,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hygrotini">Hygrotini</taxonomicName>
and several morphological characters, the genus (which corresponds to Clade B in 
<figureCitation box="[610,674,1765,1790]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[188,1357,201,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[185,1388,195,1940]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogeny of Hygrotini, modified from Villastrigo et al. (in press). Numbers above nodes are bootstrap support values. Note that here the former generic and subgeneric names are still used." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/884768/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) is subdivided into four clades corresponding to the following four subgenera: clade B1 = subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[524,650,1801,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Coelambus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[524,650,1801,1826]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Coelambus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, clade B2 = subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[909,1048,1801,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hyphoporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[909,1048,1801,1826]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Hyphoporus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, clade B3 = subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Fery, 2017" authorityName="Fery" authorityYear="2017" box="[1307,1410,1802,1825]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hygrotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto" status="s. str.">
<emphasis box="[1307,1410,1802,1825]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Hygrotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="19" pageNumber="518" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and clade B4 = 
<emphasis box="[367,512,1837,1862]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">Leptolambus</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[519,640,1837,1862]" pageId="19" pageNumber="518">n. subgen.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
